    summary: 'Oil paint applied so thickly that brushstrokes leave a sculptural, three-dimensional texture. Van Gogh\'s turbulent skies are built in dense ridges that catch raking light dynamically — the painted surface itself becomes as expressive as the subject. Rembrandt used selective impasto in highlights to draw the eye.',
    artists: ['Van Gogh', 'Rembrandt', 'Monet', 'Courbet', 'Frank Auerbach'],
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Pointillism',
    subtitle: 'Optical Colour Mixing',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/7d/A_Sunday_on_La_Grande_Jatte%2C_Georges_Seurat%2C_1884.jpg/1280px-A_Sunday_on_La_Grande_Jatte%2C_Georges_Seurat%2C_1884.jpg',
    summary: 'Tiny dots of pure unmixed colour placed side by side — the viewer\'s eye blends them optically at a distance into luminous, vibrating tones. Seurat\'s "La Grande Jatte" (1884–86) was constructed from thousands of touches over years. The method was grounded in colour science by theorists Chevreul and Rood.',
    artists: ['Georges Seurat', 'Paul Signac', 'Henri-Edmond Cross'],
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Collage',
    subtitle: 'Assembled Fragments',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/18/Juan_Gris_-_Portrait_of_Pablo_Picasso_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg/800px-Juan_Gris_-_Portrait_of_Pablo_Picasso_-_Google_Art_Project.jpg',
    summary: 'Picasso and Braque incorporated newspaper clippings and printed labels into Synthetic Cubist works (1912), blurring the line between fine art and everyday matter. Höch and Heartfield weaponized photomontage as political critique of Weimar Germany. Cornell enclosed enigmatic ephemera in dreamlike shadow boxes.',
    artists: ['Picasso', 'Braque', 'Kurt Schwitters', 'Hannah Höch', 'Joseph Cornell'],
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Tempera',
    subtitle: 'Egg & Pigment',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/26/Sandro_Botticelli_046.jpg/1280px-Sandro_Botticelli_046.jpg',
    summary: 'Egg tempera — pigment suspended in egg yolk — dominated European panel painting for two centuries. It dries in seconds and must be built through fine hatching strokes, creating a crystalline, graphic surface. Botticelli\'s "Birth of Venus" is inseparable from the medium\'s luminous linearity.',
    artists: ['Giotto', 'Duccio', 'Botticelli', 'Piero della Francesca', 'Andrew Wyeth'],
  },
  {
    category: 'techniques',
    title: 'Encaustic',
    subtitle: 'Molten Wax',
    image: 'https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/40/Fayum_egyptian_funerary_portrait_1627_NAMAthens.jpg/600px-Fayum_egyptian_funerary_portrait_1627_NAMAthens.jpg',
    summary: 'Heated beeswax mixed with pigment and resin, applied hot and fused to a rigid surface. The Fayum mummy portraits (1st–3rd century CE) are astonishingly lifelike faces of extraordinary psychological immediacy. Jasper Johns revived encaustic in the 1950s, exploiting wax\'s translucency to layer meaning.',
    artists: ['Anonymous Fayum masters', 'Jasper Johns'],
  },
];

